    <patterns>
      <pattern name="Existing structured-output (non-streaming) pattern" location="src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/OpenAiClient.cs">
        `GetStructuredCompletionAsync&lt;T&gt;()` + `GetStructuredCompletionRawAsync()` already use
        `ChatResponseFormat.CreateJsonSchemaFormat(schemaName, jsonSchema, jsonSchemaIsStrict: true)`
        with `CompleteChatAsync`. R5 keeps this exact response-format configuration but switches
        to `CompleteChatStreamingAsync` so the JSON arrives as `StreamingChatCompletionUpdate`
        tokens. The new helper consumes those tokens and emits `FieldDelta` events as JSON paths
        complete (or open, depending on spike outcome).
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="Existing plain-text streaming pattern" location="src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/OpenAiClient.cs">
        `StreamCompletionAsync()` shows the streaming-iteration shape: wrap
        `chatClient.CompleteChatStreamingAsync(...)` in circuit-breaker; iterate
        `streamingResult.WithCancellation(ct)` → each `update.ContentUpdate` part yields
        `contentPart.Text`. R5's new path layers an incremental JSON parser on top of this
        same iteration to surface field-boundary events.
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="Playbook execution streaming envelope" location="src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/AnalysisOrchestrationService.cs">
        `ExecutePlaybookAsync` is the entry-point used by Summarize. It yields
        `AnalysisStreamChunk` events (`Metadata`, `TextChunk`, etc.). R5 emits `AnalysisChunk`
        `FieldDelta` events through this same pipeline (envelope shape per task 005).
        The new behavior plugs into the Summarize tool/node execution; the orchestrator
        signature does not change.
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="Streaming tool handler opt-in interface" location="src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/IStreamingAnalysisToolHandler.cs">
        `IStreamingAnalysisToolHandler` extends `IAnalysisToolHandler` for per-token
        streaming. R5 may upgrade `SummaryHandler` (or its node-executor wrapper) to
        implement `IStreamingAnalysisToolHandler` and emit `ToolStreamEvent.Token` events
        carrying field-tagged JSON deltas. Verify whether to extend `ToolStreamEvent` with
        a new `FieldDelta` variant or piggyback on `Token(text)`; record decision in task notes.
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="Incremental JSON parser implementation reference" location="(no in-repo equivalent — new helper)">
        Read approaches: `System.Text.Json.Utf8JsonReader` over a growing buffer; OR a small
        state machine that scans for top-level field-name tokens + closing-quote / closing-brace.
        For the Summarize schema (flat-ish: `summary` string, `tldr` array of strings, `keywords`
        string, `entities` object), a state machine keyed on JSON path
        (`$.tldr[0]`, `$.summary`, `$.keywords`, `$.entities.organizations[0]`, ...) is sufficient.
        Spike validates whether the granularity is per-character, per-token, or per-field-complete.
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="DI registration via feature module" location="src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Infrastructure/DI/AnalysisServicesModule.cs">
        Per ADR-010 + R5 CLAUDE.md §3.3: register any new helper inside the existing
        `AnalysisServicesModule.cs` feature module. Concrete class; no interface unless a
        test seam demands it.
      </pattern>
    </patterns>
  </knowledge>

  <context>
    <background>
      R5 ships a chat-driven "Summarize a Document" vertical slice. The user experience
      requires ChatGPT/Claude-style progressive rendering of the structured summary
      (TL;DR appears first as a "cursor", then summary prose fills in token-by-token,
      then per-file highlights, then call-to-action). The existing wizard `Summarize`
      playbook today returns a final `DocumentAnalysisResult` only at stream end — there
      is no progressive structured-field emission. R5 task 005 introduces the
      `AnalysisChunk.FieldDelta` variant (additive SSE event type, `Type = "delta"`,
      with a `FieldDelta` record carrying `Path`, `Content`, `Sequence`). THIS task wires
      that envelope to the actual Summarize execution path so events fire in order as
      Azure OpenAI streams JSON tokens.

      The risk is in the AI layer: Azure OpenAI Structured Outputs (JSON Schema strict
      mode) is documented to support streaming, BUT empirically (per plan.md High-Risk
      Items row 1) the granularity of streamed JSON tokens may not match R5's needs.
      Possible failure modes: (a) Azure streams the full structured response at end of
      stream (defeating the purpose); (b) Azure streams character-by-character but
      JSON-path inference at character granularity is fragile; (c) JSON Schema strict
      mode disables streaming entirely. The spike at Step A resolves this empirically.
    </background>
    <dependencies>
      <dependency task="005" status="not-started">
        Task 005 (D1-05) introduces the `AnalysisChunk.FieldDelta` variant + `FieldDelta`
        record. This task EMITS those events through the Summarize execution path.
        Task 005 MUST be complete before this task starts.
      </dependency>
    </dependencies>
    <related-work>
      <item>
        Task 010 (D2-01) deploys the "Summarize Document for Chat" `sprk_analysisaction`
        seed. The action's JPS-formatted system prompt + output schema MUST align with
        the JSON parser's expected paths. Any schema field additions surfaced during
        this task should be communicated to task 010 via task notes.
      </item>
      <item>
        Task 017 (D2-07) implements `StructuredOutputStreamWidget` — the Workspace
        consumer of these `FieldDelta` events. The widget reads `Path` + `Content` to
        render progressively. Path conventions established here (`$.tldr[0]`, `$.summary`,
        etc.) become the widget's input contract.
      </item>
      <item>
        Tasks 012, 014 (D2-03 SessionSummarizeOrchestrator + D2-04 endpoint) depend on
        this task as the underlying streaming engine.
      </item>
      <item>
        Task 020 (D2-11 chat-pane orchestration UX) ultimately renders the streaming
        result; this is the producer.
      </item>
      <item>
        Wizard back-compat: `src/solutions/LegalWorkspace/src/components/SummarizeFiles/summarizeService.ts`
        is the existing consumer that ignores `delta` events. Verify it tolerates the
        new event type without behavior change.
      </item>
    </related-work>
  </context>

  <steps>
    <step order="0" name="Context Check + RIGOR LEVEL declaration">
      Check context usage per CLAUDE.md §5. If &gt; 70%, create handoff summary and request `/compact`.
      Declare:
      ```
      🔒 RIGOR LEVEL: FULL
      📋 REASON: BFF code change + AI infrastructure + new helper class + HIGH-RISK task per plan.md
      📖 PROTOCOL STEPS TO EXECUTE: Step 0 → Step 1 → ... → Step A (spike) → ... → Step 9.5 (quality gates) → Step 10
      Proceeding with Step 0...
      ```
    </step>
    <step order="1" name="Review Progress + Verify Dependency">
      Read `tasks/TASK-INDEX.md`. Confirm task 006 status is 🔲. Confirm task 005 status is ✅
      (FieldDelta variant lands first). If 005 is still 🔲, STOP and report blocker.
      Read `current-task.md` to confirm no prior R5 task is in flight. Read project README
      for project status.
    </step>
    <step order="2" name="Gather Resources">
      Read every file in &lt;inputs&gt; and &lt;knowledge&gt;. Specifically extract:
      (a) The current `AnalysisChunk` envelope shape AFTER task 005 — confirm `Type = "delta"`
          and the `FieldDelta` record are present.
      (b) `OpenAiClient.GetStructuredCompletionAsync&lt;T&gt;` + `GetStructuredCompletionRawAsync`
          to understand current Structured Outputs configuration (`CreateJsonSchemaFormat`,
          `jsonSchemaIsStrict: true`).
      (c) `OpenAiClient.StreamCompletionAsync` to see streaming iteration pattern.
      (d) `AnalysisOrchestrationService.ExecutePlaybookAsync` to locate where the Summarize
          tool/node fires and how `AnalysisStreamChunk` events flow today.
      (e) `IStreamingAnalysisToolHandler` to understand the per-token streaming opt-in.
      (f) `SummaryHandler` to understand the current non-streaming Summarize implementation.
      (g) `DocumentAnalysisResult` to confirm the target output schema.
      (h) `summarizeService.ts` (wizard consumer) to verify back-compat behavior.
      Record the exact code-path that today drives Summarize (tool handler vs node executor)
      in task notes. THIS is the path you will extend.
    </step>
    <step order="3" name="Plan Implementation (file inventory + decisions)">
      Produce a plan document at `notes/task-006-implementation-plan.md` covering:
      (a) Which files will be CREATED (e.g., `Services/Ai/Streaming/IncrementalJsonParser.cs`,
          `Services/Ai/Streaming/StructuredOutputStreamingService.cs`).
      (b) Which files will be MODIFIED (e.g., `OpenAiClient.cs` to add a streaming structured-output
          method; `SummaryHandler.cs` or its node-executor wrapper to use the streaming variant;
          `AnalysisServicesModule.cs` for DI registration).
      (c) JSON-path conventions for `FieldDelta.Path`: `$.tldr[0]`, `$.summary`, `$.keywords`,
          `$.entities.organizations[0]`, etc.
      (d) Field-emission ordering target: TL;DR → summary → keywords → entities. (Note:
          Azure OpenAI may emit in JSON-property-declaration order; the JSON schema declared in
          `DocumentAnalysisResult.cs` is summary first. If R5 wants TL;DR first as
          UX requirement, REORDER the schema property declarations to match — record decision.)
      (e) Open questions that the spike (Step A) will answer.
    </step>
    <step order="A" name="SPIKE: validate Structured Outputs streaming behavior (HIGH-RISK)">
      Per plan.md High-Risk Items row 1, BEFORE committing to one path, run a small spike.
      Spike scope (~2–3 hours, throwaway code in `notes/spikes/task-006-structured-outputs/`):
      (1) Write a minimal console / test harness that calls Azure OpenAI on Spaarke Dev with:
          - Structured Outputs (JSON Schema strict mode) — same `CreateJsonSchemaFormat` config
            as existing `GetStructuredCompletionRawAsync`.
          - `CompleteChatStreamingAsync` (NOT `CompleteChatAsync`).
          - A trimmed Summarize-style schema (summary string, tldr array of strings,
            keywords string).
          - A representative legal-document prompt.
      (2) Log every `StreamingChatCompletionUpdate.ContentUpdate[*].Text` token to console,
          accumulating into a string buffer.
      (3) Observe + record:
          - Does Azure stream partial JSON tokens? (yes/no/character-level/word-level/field-level)
          - Is the stream syntactically valid JSON at every intermediate state?
            (Likely not — partial strings have open quotes; the parser must tolerate this.)
          - Can a simple state machine detect field-boundary events
            (`"tldr":` opens → `]` closes) at acceptable granularity?
          - What is the TTFB latency? (target: &lt; 500ms per NFR-01)
          - If Structured Outputs streaming returns only the FINAL full record, the spike fails.
      (4) ALSO test Function Calling fallback path:
          - Define a `record_summary` function whose parameters ARE the Summarize schema.
          - Stream via `CompleteChatStreamingAsync` and observe tool-call argument streaming.
      (5) Write `notes/task-006-spike-results.md` with:
          - Outcome: PATH A (Structured Outputs streaming + incremental JSON parser) OR
            PATH B (Function Calling with manual JSON parse).
          - Evidence: representative log excerpts + TTFB measurement + character-granularity
            assessment.
          - Decision rationale: which path is cheaper to implement, more robust, more
            future-proof.
          - Known risks / caveats for the chosen path.
      (6) Checkpoint via `context-handoff` skill after spike completion.

      The spike outcome DRIVES the implementation in Steps 4–7. If the spike reveals
      a third unexpected option (e.g., Azure SDK exposes a structured-streaming helper
      we missed), document + escalate to operator per CLAUDE.md §6 before proceeding.
    </step>
    <step order="4" name="Implement IncrementalJsonParser helper">
      Create `src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/Streaming/IncrementalJsonParser.cs`
      (or equivalent path per Step 3 plan). Behavior:
      - Accepts a stream of partial JSON text via `Append(string token)`.
      - Maintains internal buffer + JSON-path state (current `$.summary`, `$.tldr[0]`, etc.).
      - Yields `FieldDeltaEvent` records carrying `(Path, Content, Sequence, IsFieldStart, IsFieldComplete)`
        as field boundaries are detected.
      - Tolerates unclosed strings / partial arrays — the parser is "best-effort";
        when a field's contents fully arrive (closing `"` or closing `]`), it emits an
        `IsFieldComplete` event.
      - On end-of-stream, attempts a final full-document parse via `JsonSerializer.Deserialize&lt;DocumentAnalysisResult&gt;`
        and returns it for the closing `AnalysisChunk.Completed(result)` event.
      - On unrecoverable parse failure, returns the raw buffer for `DocumentAnalysisResult.Fallback(rawResponse)`.
      Implementation may use `System.Text.Json.Utf8JsonReader` with `bytesConsumed` /
      `isFinalBlock` semantics, OR a custom state machine — pick the simpler approach
      per spike outcome. Unit-test thoroughly (Step 5 below).

      IF spike outcome is PATH B (Function Calling): instead, parser consumes tool-call
      argument deltas from `StreamingChatCompletionUpdate.ToolCallUpdates` and emits the
      same `FieldDeltaEvent` shape so the downstream service is path-agnostic.
    </step>
    <step order="5" name="Wire incremental parser into Summarize execution path">
      Extend the Summarize execution code path (per Step 2 finding — either `SummaryHandler` /
      its node-executor wrapper, or `AnalysisOrchestrationService.ExecutePlaybookAsync`'s
      Summarize-tool branch):
      (a) Add a new method on `OpenAiClient` (e.g., `StreamStructuredCompletionAsync`) that
          combines `CreateJsonSchemaFormat(strict: true)` + `CompleteChatStreamingAsync`
          + circuit-breaker wrapping (mirrors `StreamCompletionAsync` shape). Yields
          `StreamingChatCompletionUpdate` tokens.
      (b) The Summarize path consumes that stream, feeds each token to
          `IncrementalJsonParser.Append(...)`, and translates each emitted
          `FieldDeltaEvent` into an `AnalysisChunk` with `Type = "delta"` + populated
          `FieldDelta` payload (per the variant added by task 005).
      (c) At end of stream, the parser returns the final `DocumentAnalysisResult` (or
          `Fallback`), which is emitted as `AnalysisChunk.Completed(result)` — UNCHANGED
          envelope shape, preserves wizard back-compat per NFR-10.
      (d) On mid-stream parse failure, emit `AnalysisChunk.FromError(...)` and terminate
          the stream gracefully.
    </step>
    <step order="6" name="Verify field-level progressive emission ordering">
      Manually run the Summarize path against a representative document on Spaarke Dev
      (use existing dev environment / playbook GUID `4a72f99c-a119-f111-8343-7ced8d1dc988`
      per FR-01 acceptance criterion). Capture the SSE event stream via browser DevTools
      or `curl --no-buffer`. Verify:
